240 77 "Discuss the relation between the effective Lyapunov exponent a
nd the Jacobian" }{TEXT 240 0 "" }}{PARA 297 "" 0 "" {TEXT 238 0 "" }}
}{EXCHG {PARA 297 "" 0 "" {TEXT 238 0 "" }}{PARA 297 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
238 565 "The effective Lyapunov exponent is built from two components:
 the eigenvalues of the (symmetric part of the) Jacobian and the pertu
rbation vector. Because of the dynamical behavior of the system, the e
igenvalues and eigenvectors will vary as a function of time in magnitu
de and orientation, respectively. Furthermore, depending on how the th
e perturbation vector is aligned with the eigenvectors, it will have i
ts own effective eigenvalue somewhere between the minimum and maximum \+
eigenvalue. Lastly, this is a function of time as well, so in general \+
the effective " }{TEXT 238 92 "Lyapunov exponent will be a non-trivial
 weighted average of all three eigenvalues over time." }{TEXT 238 0 ""
 }}{PARA 297 "" 0 "" {TEXT 238 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 300 "> " 0 "" 
